Three agents — a yard operator who dispatches the inbound and outbound robotic trucks, a logistics planner who holds the dynamic yard map, and a crane operator who executes one physical crane move per tool call — coordinate over a shared link channel to place one to three incoming containers into their correct slots each round across {{ round_count }} rounds. Customs inspectors are waiting at each target slot: every container must reach its slot within a fixed {{ time_budget_seconds }}-second inspection window or the inspection is missed and the round fails. Every character sent on the link channel costs one simulated second against that window.

The yard operator sees each incoming container's ID one at a time and only learns the next ID after the previous container has been placed. The logistics planner alone sees the round's yard map: which crane stations are active, the two transfer pads at each station, which stacks each station can reach, the current four-stack layout, and the shift manifest of scheduled inbound containers paired with their target slots. The planner does not know which scheduled container is on the current inbound truck and must wait for the yard operator to report each one before constructing the plan for it. The crane operator sees only their crane and the link channel; they cannot solve a round on their own. Some deliveries need a buried-slot reshuffle: one blocker container must be lifted onto a separate outbound truck (which leaves loaded) before the inbound truck's container can be placed.

Round success requires every scheduled delivery to complete with its expected trucks (the inbound truck always; the outbound truck whenever the target slot is already occupied, arriving empty), every expected crane move executed in the right order by the right container, and the inspection window not exhausted.
